    """

            use:

                       config = "/home/localuser/.datacube.conf")
            dc.list_products()
            
        to see all the available products
        
        utils_foler: The directory that has the data_access_api.py this is usually in datacube_notebooks
        
        config file: The datacube configuration file
        
    
    """
    def __init__(self,product, utils_folder ='/home/local/AMA-INC/amelbag/aviv_notebook_server/GANs/scpd/data_cube_utilities/data_access_api.py',config_file = "/home/localuser/.datacube.conf" ):
        self.product= product
        print(self.product)
        loader = importlib.machinery.SourceFileLoader('utils', utils_folder)
        handle = loader.load_module('utils')
        self.api = handle.DataAccessApi(config=config_file)
        self.meta_data = self.api.get_datacube_metadata(product = self.product)
        self.dc = datacube.Datacube(app    = "my_random_app",
                       config = "/home/localuser/.datacube.conf")
        
    
    def show_extents(self,MAPPING = True):
        import folium
        """
        Shows all available extents of the specified product"""
        lats = self.meta_data['lat_extents']
        lons =self.meta_data['lon_extents']
        times = self.meta_data['time_extents']
        print("For: ", str(self.product))
        print('The latitude extents are ' + str(lats))
        print('The longitude extents are ' + str(lons))
        print('The time extents are ' + str(times))
        
        #returns the map as well
        if MAPPING == True:
            mapa = folium.Map([np.mean(lats), np.mean(lons)], zoom_start=13,tiles='Stamen Terrain')
            mapa.fit_bounds([[lats[0],lons[0]],[lats[1],lons[1]]])
            folium.Marker([lats[0],lons[0]]).add_to(mapa)
            folium.Marker([lats[0],lons[1]]).add_to(mapa)
            folium.Marker([lats[1],lons[0]]).add_to(mapa)
            folium.Marker([lats[1],lons[1]]).add_to(mapa)
            return [lats,lons,times, mapa]
        
        #Else don't return the map
        return [lats,lons,times]

Localized Linear Histogram Match(LLHM)¶

Based off the paper: SLC Gap-Filled Products Phase One Methodology by Scaramuzza et al

In May 2003 the Scan Line Corrector on the Landsat 7 failed. The Scan line corrector is responsible for compensating for the forward motion of the sattelite. Without the compensator you are left with the black bands which comprise around 22% of all the LS7 data. There are many ways to fill these gaps. In this series we will explain the various methods.

In [92]:
Image('SLCGAP.JPG')
Out[92]:

Number 1 in the SLC Band Gap Filling Series¶

Before we start let's show an example:¶

In [14]:
Image('First.JPG')
Out[14]:

This method is the simplest of all methods. And requires a scene from prior to the failure in 2003.¶

$$Y\approx GX+B$$

$\text{where:}\\ G =\text{the bias used to histogram match the SLC-On image to the SLC-off image.} \\ B = \text{ the bias used to histogram match the SLC-On image to the SLC-off image.} \\ X = \text{SLC-On Scene (No gaps)} \\ Y = \text{SLC-Off Scene (gaps)} $

$\text{where: } \\ G = \frac{\sigma_y}{\sigma_x} \\ B = \bar{Y} - G \bar{X} \\ $

$ \sigma_x = \text{the standard deviation of data in SLC-on image X.} \\ \sigma_y = \text{the standard deviation of data in SLC-off image Y.} \\ \bar{X} = \text{The mean of the SLC-On scene array} \\ \bar{Y} = \text{The mean of the SLC-Off scene array} $

One thing to note is that you don't use the pixels that are not known in the calculation of the variables.

Using Datacube we need to see the data that we want.¶

def normalized_plot(i):
    red = np.array(dataset['red'][i])
    green = np.array(dataset['green'][i])
    blue =np.array(dataset['blue'][i])
    mask_data = (red ==-9999)
    np.putmask(red,mask_data,0)
    np.putmask(green,mask_data,0)
    np.putmask(blue,mask_data,0)
    #plt.imshow(mask_data)
    im = np.dstack([red/np.max(green),red/np.max(green),blue/np.max(blue)])
    plt.imshow(im)
    return im

def make_std_graph(im,size= 8):
    [maxX, maxY,_] = im.shape
    std_arr = np.zeros((maxX,maxY,3))
    mu_arr  = np.zeros((maxX,maxY,3))
    for k in range(3):    
        for i in range(0,maxX):
            for j in range(0,maxY):
                mas = np.ma.array(im[np.max([0,i-size]):np.min([maxX,i+size]),np.max([0,j-size]):np.min([j+size,maxY]),k], mask=masks[np.max([0,i-size]):np.min([maxX,i+size]),np.max([0,j-size]):np.min([j+size,maxY]),k])
                mas = np.array(mas[~mas.mask])
                s = mas.flatten()
                std_arr[i,j,k] = s.std()
                mu_arr[i,j,k] = s.mean()
    return std_arr,mu_arr
